  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "To solve this problem, we can use Bayes' theorem. Let's define the following:\n\n- Let \\( A \\) be the event that all balls are white.\n- Let \\( B \\) be the event that two balls drawn from the bag are white.\n\nWe need to calculate \\( P(A \\mid B) \\), the probability that all balls are white given that two drawn balls are white.\n\n### Step 1: Determine the possible configurations of the balls.\nAssume there are two cases for the configuration of the balls:\n1. **Case 1:** All 4 balls are white (WWWW).\n2. **Case 2:** There are 3 white balls and 1 black ball (WWWB).\n3. **Case 3:** There are 2 white balls and 2 black balls (WWBB).\n4. **Case 4:** There are 1 white ball and 3 black balls (WBBB).\n5. **Case 5:** All 4 balls are black (BBBB).\n\n### Step 2: Calculate the probabilities of drawing 2 white balls.\nWe also need the probability of drawing 2 white balls, \\( P(B \\mid A) \\), for each configuration of the balls.\n\n- **Case 1:** \\( P(B \\mid A) = P(B \\mid \\text{WWWW}) = 1 \\) (Because both drawn balls will definitely be white.)\n- **Case 2:** \\( P(B \\mid \\text{WWW}) = \\frac{3}{4} \\cdot \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{1}{2} \\) (We choose 2 white from 3 total white.)\n- **Case 3:** \\( P(B \\mid \\text{WWBB}) = \\frac{2}{4} \\cdot \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{1}{6} \\) (We choose 2 white balls from 2 total white.)\n- **Case 4:** \\( P(B \\mid \\text{WBBB}) = 0 \\) (We can't pick 2 white balls.)\n- **Case 5:** \\( P(B \\mid \\text{BBBB}) = 0 \\) (We can't pick 2 white balls.)\n\n### Step 3: Assuming equal prior probabilities.\nLet\u2019s assume that each configuration is equally likely, which means dealing with a total of 5 configurations: \n\n- \\( P(\\text{WWWW}) = \\frac{1}{5} \\)\n- \\( P(\\text{WWW}) = \\frac{1}{5} \\)\n- \\( P(\\text{WWBB}) = \\frac{1}{5} \\)\n- \\( P(\\text{WBBB}) = \\frac{1}{5} \\)\n- \\( P(\\text{BBBB}) = \\frac{1}{5} \\)\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the overall probability of \\( B \\).\nUsing the law of total probability:\n\n\\[\nP(B) = P(B \\mid A) \\cdot P(A) + P(B \\mid \\text{WWW}) \\cdot P(\\text{WWW}) + P(B \\mid \\text{WWBB}) \\cdot P(\\text{WWBB}) + P(B \\mid \\text{WBBB}) \\cdot P(\\text{WBBB}) + P(B \\mid \\text{BBBB}) \\cdot P(\\text{BBBB})\n\\]\n\nSubstituting values:\n\n\\[\nP(B) = 1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{1}{6} \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + 0 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + 0 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5}\n\\]\n\nCalculating this gives:\n\n\\[\nP(B) = \\frac{1}{5} + \\frac{1}{10} + \\frac{1}{30} = \\frac{6 + 3 + 1}{30} = \\frac{10}{30} = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Calculate \\( P(A \\mid B) \\) using Bayes\u2019 theorem.\n\\[\nP(A \\mid B) = \\frac{P(B \\mid A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)}\n\\]\nSubstituting values gives:\n\n\\[\nP(A \\mid B) = \\frac{1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5}}{\\frac{1}{3}} = \\frac{3}{5}\n\\]\n\nThus, the final result is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{3}{5}}\n\\] \n\nSo, the probability that all balls are white given that two drawn balls are white is \\( \\frac{3}{5} \\).",
